    notes:
      "## The Two-Tier Selank Hierarchy\n\n**Base Selank:**\n- Original Tuftsin analog (Thr-Lys-Pro-Arg-Pro-Gly-Pro)\n- Plasma half-life ~2 hours\n- Lower cost\n- Most extensively studied form in Russian pharmaceutical research\n- More frequent dosing required\n\n**N-Acetyl Selank Amidate (this entry):**\n- Stability-modified analog with N-acetyl + C-amide\n- Plasma half-life substantially extended\n- Most-used research peptide form\n- Practical dosing convenience\n- Best balance for most research-protocol users\n\n## Beginner Protocol\n200mcg IM, subQ, or intranasal × first dose to assess tolerance. If well-tolerated, advance to 300mcg/dose daily × 4 weeks. Track: anxiety levels, mood, sleep quality, cognitive function. The anxiolytic effect is often subjectively perceptible within 30-60 minutes of dose.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\n**The Russian classical Selank+Semax pairing (the central use case):**\n- N-Acetyl Selank Amidate 300mcg/dose\n- N-Acetyl Semax Amidate 300mcg/dose AM cycled 2-on/2-off\n- Both administered AM concurrently (or Selank can be afternoon/evening for users wanting separate timing)\n- The pairing addresses anxiety + cognitive performance simultaneously — neither compound alone provides the dual effect\n- Selank's calming offsets Semax's stimulating profile, allowing more comfortable cognitive enhancement\n- Selank's anxiolytic effect is the central distinguishing benefit; Semax's BDNF upregulation is the central distinguishing benefit; the combination is mechanistically rational\n\n**Anxiety priority protocol:** N-Acetyl Selank Amidate 300mcg/day continuous + magnesium glycinate 400mg PM + L-theanine 200mg AM/PM + glycine 3g pre-bed for comprehensive anxiolytic foundation. Compatible with SSRIs / SNRIs at standard doses; coordinate with prescriber.\n\n**Anxiety-driven insomnia protocol:** N-Acetyl Selank Amidate 300mcg PM + magnesium glycinate 400mg pre-bed + glycine 3g pre-bed + low-dose melatonin (0.3mg Pierpaoli physiological dose). Selank's anxiolytic effect addresses the anxiety component of sleep difficulty; magnesium / glycine / melatonin address sleep architecture directly.\n\n## Selank vs Benzodiazepines — Decision Frame\n\nSelank is conceptually appealing as benzodiazepine alternative for chronic anxiety. The honest comparison:\n\n**Selank advantages:**\n- No dependence, no withdrawal\n- No cognitive impairment\n- No motor impairment\n- BDNF upregulation provides neurotrophic benefit\n- Research peptide profile (no controlled substance status)\n\n**Benzodiazepine advantages:**\n- Substantially more potent acute anxiolytic effect for severe anxiety\n- FDA-approved with extensive RCT base\n- Insurance-covered, prescription-available\n- Faster onset (~30 min vs ~30-60 min)\n- Established protocols for clinical use\n\n**Practical:** for severe acute anxiety or panic disorder, benzodiazepines remain the more potent acute intervention. For chronic mild-to-moderate anxiety where the dependence/cognitive-impairment profile of benzodiazepines is undesirable, Selank fits a useful role. Many users running comprehensive anxiety management combine both modalities — benzodiazepines for acute severe events, Selank for daily baseline anxiolytic support — under prescriber coordination.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\n30mg lyophilized vial; reconstitute with 3ml bacteriostatic water → 10mg/ml working concentration. IM, subQ, or intranasal routes. Refrigerate reconstituted; use within 28–30 days.\n\n## Synergies\n**N-Acetyl Semax Amidate:** the classical Russian cognitive+calm pairing. **Magnesium glycinate:** complementary calming foundation. **L-theanine:** complementary alpha-wave / glutamate-modulation anxiolytic. **Glycine:** complementary inhibitory neurotransmitter mechanism. **Lion's Mane:** complementary neurotrophic mechanism (NGF + BDNF support layered). **Bacopa Monnieri:** complementary anxiolytic + cognitive mechanism. **Bromantane:** complementary actoprotector mechanism for stress resilience.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nMjasoedov 1996, 2008 — Russian clinical research on Selank for anxiety disorders. Kozlovskaya 2003 — anxiolytic effects characterization. Russian pharmaceutical regulatory approval establishes the clinical evidence base; the N-Acetyl Amidate analog has less direct clinical evidence but mechanism extrapolates from base Selank.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized — multifactorial anxiolytic via GABA / serotonin / dopamine / enkephalin pathways; BDNF upregulation; immunomodulatory effects. Russian pharmaceutical regulatory backing for base Selank establishes safety and efficacy in pharmaceutical contexts. The amidate analog has mechanistic extrapolation rather than direct clinical evidence.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid Russian clinical evidence base for base Selank; mechanism well-characterized; the amidate analog mechanistically extrapolates. Anecdote: extensive use in nootropic and biohacking communities; subjective anxiolytic effects often perceptible within 30-60 minutes; pairs with Semax in classical Russian protocol. Decision frame: anxiolytic peptide with substantially better tolerability profile than benzodiazepines for chronic use; pairs with N-Acetyl Semax Amidate for cognitive+calm dual profile; useful component of comprehensive anxiety management; not a replacement for benzodiazepines in severe acute anxiety / panic disorder contexts but reasonable adjunct or chronic baseline option.",
