    notes:
      "## The Human Evidence Gap — Honest Framing\n\nDihexa occupies an unusual position in the catalog: extraordinary preclinical evidence, essentially absent human clinical evidence. The honest framing matters:\n\n**What the preclinical evidence shows:**\n- HGF/c-Met activation 7+ orders of magnitude more potent than parent angiotensin IV\n- Synaptogenesis substantially exceeding BDNF and other cognitive enhancement mechanisms\n- Cognitive improvements in animal models of Alzheimer's, aging, learning/memory tasks\n- Neuroprotective effects in stroke, TBI, neurodegeneration models\n- The Joe Harding laboratory at Washington State University has produced substantial peer-reviewed research\n\n**What the human evidence shows:**\n- No completed Phase I, II, or III clinical trials\n- No pharmaceutical development pipeline currently advancing the compound\n- Research peptide community use is the primary human exposure base\n- No long-term safety data\n- No human RCT data on cognitive enhancement\n\n**Why the gap exists:**\n- Pharmaceutical development of cognitive enhancers has been challenging across the industry\n- Alzheimer's drug development specifically has been a graveyard for promising preclinical compounds\n- Patent / commercial development decisions affect which compounds advance to human trials\n- Research peptide community use proceeds without waiting for pharmaceutical development\n\n**Practical position for users:**\n- The mechanism is mechanistically interesting and animal evidence is robust\n- Human clinical evidence is genuinely absent\n- Empirical individual trial is reasonable for users wanting to evaluate the mechanism in their own experience\n- Should not be marketed or evaluated as if human RCT evidence existed\n- Long-term effects on human brain structure are unknown\n\nThis honest framing parallels the Khavinson class where Russian research evidence is substantial but Western replication limited. Dihexa's gap is even larger — animal model evidence is solid but human evidence is absent rather than just limited.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\n5mg/day × 1 week (tolerance), then 8mg/day. Sublingual oil or oral capsule typical. Track cognitive function (memory, learning, processing speed) at baseline and 8-12 weeks. Effects often subtle and accumulate over weeks; users expecting acute stimulant-like effects will be disappointed. The mechanism (synaptogenesis) operates on a different timescale.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\n**Comprehensive cognitive enhancement stack:** Dihexa 8-12mg/day + N-Acetyl Semax Amidate 300mcg AM cycled 2-on/2-off (overlap HGF/c-Met mechanism + add BDNF/NGF) + Lion's Mane 1000mg/day continuous (complementary NGF/BDNF) + Alpha-GPC 600mg/day continuous (cholinergic substrate) + omega-3 high-DHA 2g/day + B-complex methylated.\n\n**Cognitive aging / mild cognitive impairment context (under prescriber coordination):** Dihexa as adjunct exploration in age-related cognitive decline — coordinate with neurologist; the mechanism is rationale-based but human clinical evidence absent for this application.\n\n**Cycling protocol:** Some users cycle Dihexa 5 days on / 2 days off or 8 weeks on / 2 weeks off; no formal cycling requirement based on current evidence; tolerance pattern not well characterized.\n\n## The Cancer Caveat — Worth Honest Discussion\n\nHGF/c-Met dysregulation is associated with several cancers — particularly some lung cancers, gastric cancers, and renal cell carcinoma. C-Met inhibitors are FDA-approved cancer drugs (crizotinib, capmatinib) for c-Met-driven malignancies.\n\nThe theoretical concern: Dihexa activates the c-Met pathway. Could this affect tumor growth in cancers driven by c-Met dysregulation?\n\n**Honest assessment:**\n- Animal model evidence does not show tumor-promoting effects at typical doses\n- The mechanism is selective for synaptogenesis effects over tumor-promoting effects in studied models\n- Human evidence is absent — neither for tumor-promoting effects nor for safety in cancer-risk populations\n- For users with active malignancy or significant cancer family history involving c-Met-associated cancers, coordinate with oncologist before use\n- For users without active cancer or significant family history, the theoretical concern is less acute but worth knowing\n\nThis is the kind of mechanism-based concern where definitive guidance isn't possible from current evidence — users should know the concern exists and weigh accordingly.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nMost commercial Dihexa is sold as oral capsules, sublingual oil, or transdermal cream. Sublingual oil bypasses first-pass hepatic metabolism. Injectable forms exist but oral viability makes injection less common than for traditional peptides. Refrigerate sublingual oil after opening per product label.\n\n## Synergies\n**Lion's Mane:** complementary NGF/BDNF mechanism. **N-Acetyl Semax Amidate:** overlap on HGF/c-Met activation; layered effects. **Alpha-GPC / CDP-Choline:** complementary cholinergic mechanism. **Bromantane:** complementary actoprotector mechanism. **Bacopa Monnieri:** complementary cognitive support.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\n**Foundational mechanism papers (Joe Harding laboratory, Washington State University):** Benoist 2014 (synaptogenesis demonstration), McCoy 2013 (HGF/c-Met activation), Wright 2008 (parent angiotensin IV characterization). Substantial preclinical evidence base in animal models for cognitive enhancement, synaptogenesis, and neuroprotection. **No human RCTs** — the central evidence-base reality.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nPreclinical mechanism well-characterized — among the most potent known cognitive enhancement mechanisms in animal models. Academic provenance via Washington State University laboratory. **Human clinical evidence essentially absent** — research peptide community use has run ahead of formal clinical evaluation. The evidence quality is genuinely mixed: outstanding preclinical / absent clinical.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: extraordinary preclinical evidence for HGF/c-Met activation and synaptogenesis; mechanistic interest is real; human RCT evidence absent. Anecdote: extensive nootropic community use; subjective effects often subtle (the synaptogenesis mechanism operates on weeks-to-months timescale); pairs with Semax in cognitive enhancement protocols. Decision frame: mechanistically fascinating compound with extraordinary preclinical evidence and minimal human clinical evidence; reasonable empirical inclusion for users wanting to evaluate the mechanism; cancer-context caveat warrants prescriber discussion for users with active malignancy or significant family history; long-term human effects unknown; should be approached with realistic expectations about evidence quality rather than as established cognitive enhancement therapy.",
